# User-facing documentation

These rules apply when **adding or editing** Markdown intended for **developers who use Golem** (consumer projects), not internal implementation notes.

User-facing documentation now lives in the Astro website docs folder at **`C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\docs`**. The site uses **Starlight** for docs. Update files there, not under this engine repo. The old engine-local `docs/public/...` paths map to `C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\docs\...`; for example, old `docs/public/clients/unity-client.md` is now `C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\docs\clients\unity-client.md`.

## Agent: efficient discovery

- **Read `C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\README.md` first** when you need repo-level docs workflow or site commands. For section layout, doc IDs, and sidebar ordering, use the front matter and Starlight navigation/config files in the website repo.
- If the user named **specific** old `docs/public/...` paths, translate them to `C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\docs\...`, then read those files and their **direct link targets** instead of rediscovering the tree.
- Open **`cmd/golem-bake`**, **`schema/`**, **`golem/`**, etc. only when **verifying behavioral claims**, adding new factual API/YAML details, or the user asked about runtime/schema, not for tone-only, formatting-only, or link-only edits.

## Agent checklist when touching docs

1. Confirm **file location** in `C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\docs` (correct section; intro stays at `docs/intro.md`). Use the website repo's Starlight navigation/config files and existing page front matter when unsure where a topic belongs.
2. Check the **opener**: does it name a situation or problem before any API? If not, rewrite the first paragraph.
3. Check **snippet placement**: does a working code example appear before any reference table? If not, reorder. Reject any method-signature table and convert it to prose or snippets.
4. Update **cross-links** if paths or titles change.
5. Refresh sidebar/category metadata in the docs repo when **pages are added/removed** or **server section order** (or other categories) change.
6. Keep prose **concise but readable**. Prefer one clear paragraph over three fragments.
7. When adding or editing a **how-to** section, include a **snippet** if it fits the rule above (wiring, config, or typical callback bodies).

## Audience and tone

- Assume readers are **competent developers** building a game server; they do not need Go 101, but **do not** write like an internal design doc for maintainers only.
- **Lead with outcomes**: what the reader can accomplish and what problem this part of the framework solves. The first paragraph of every page should answer "why do I care about this?" before touching any API.
- **Teach usage, not internals**: explain what the developer calls and what they get back, not how the framework implements it. A reader should leave knowing how to use a feature, not how it works under the hood.
- **Open with the situation, not the definition.** Bad: "The registry is a thread-safe store that...". Good: "The registry is where your live entities are tracked. You add them when players spawn, mutate them each tick, and remove them when they leave." Use-case framing always comes before API tables.
- The **overview / intro** page should **sell** the toolkit: ticks, authoritative state, YAML to protobuf, deltas, commands, ownership, then link to deeper pages. Do not name competing products to contrast unless the user asks.
- **Factual API behavior** (e.g. "returns nil when unchanged", "Run returns an error if no removal serializer is set") is fine and important; include it, but after the use-case context.
- Do not use em dashes in documentation prose. Use commas, semicolons, parentheses, or separate sentences instead.
- Avoid **defensive "we do not provide X"** lists unless there is a real recurring confusion.
- Use **numbered workflows** where they help scanning; **concept tables** only when they add something a short paragraph would not.

## Structure

- Prefer the existing **section folders** under `C:\Demiurgos\web\golem-engine-website\docs`: **Getting started**, **Configuration & schema**, **Code generation**, **Server & simulation**, **Physics**, **Clients & networking**.
- Update Starlight sidebar/navigation configuration when creating a **new** sidebar category or changing category order.
- Each page: YAML front matter with **`title`** and Starlight-compatible ordering metadata when the page needs explicit sidebar order.
- Use **relative links** between pages (e.g. `../server/registry.md` from `clients/`) so the tree stays portable within the Astro site.
- Prefer **short, compilable-looking snippets** (YAML, Go, TS, shell) wherever they clarify **how to use** a feature, especially wiring (**`golem.yaml`**, **`Server`** + **`Listener`**, **`CommandRouter`**, **`EntityManager`**). Use **`example.com/mygame/...`** placeholders and note when names come from the user's schemas. When behavior is schema-specific, say so instead of inventing APIs.
- Put the **working example or minimal snippet first**, then the reference table. Readers scan to the first code block; the table answers follow-up questions.

## Accuracy

- Documentation must match **current public behavior** in `cmd/golem-bake`, `schema/`, `codegen/`, `golem/`, and `golem/registry/`. If the code changes, **update the docs** in the same change when practical.
- Do not document unexported details unless they are essential; prefer **user-visible APIs** and **YAML keys**.

## Coverage expectations

- **End-to-end wiring**: When explaining how the server and net layer fit together, link or mirror **`docs/getting-started/minimal-server.md`** in the docs repo (or keep that file as the single canonical **`main`** sketch) so readers see **`Server`**, **`Listener`**, **`OnUpdates`**, **`SetRemovalSerializer`**, and optional **`OnMessage`** in one place.
- **`golem.yaml` imports**: **`go-server`** and **`js-client`** get message types and marshal/unmarshal code from `golem-bake` in the integration output (plus optional **`entities.proto`** for reference). **`golem_import`** is the **Go import path** to a package named **`golem`** for **`go-server`** (defaults to **`github.com/demiurgos-hub/golem-engine/golem`**; thin re-export also works), and the **npm package specifier** for **`js-client`** (defaults to **`golem-engine`**). **Do not** imply users must invent a wrapper; direct dependency is fine.
- **Loop behavior** (`golem/loop.go`): **`Run`** returns errors from **`FlushAll`**, removal serialization, and missing removal serializer; there is **no** panic recovery in **`OnTick`** / **`OnUpdates`**. Mention this when documenting runtime expectations.
- **Schema edge cases**: Empty **`fields`** on a command is **valid** when `BuildCommandData` allows it. Confirm in `schema/` before stating "allowed" or "forbidden."

## What to avoid

- **Release-notes framing in permanent docs.** Never write pages as if announcing a feature to someone who had an older version. Forbidden patterns: "can now", "now includes/exports/supports", "What changed", "Do existing games need to change?", "Recommended upgrade path", "update to a version that includes". Write every page as if it describes how the feature has always worked, because to a reader arriving from search or the sidebar, it has.
- **"X is a Y that Z" openers** read as API reference, not teaching material. Start with what the developer is trying to do, then name the thing that helps them do it.
- **No function or method signature tables.** Do not list method signatures (`CreateEntity(Entity, owner ...int64) error`, etc.) in tables or bullet lists. Show usage through code snippets and prose. Signature reference belongs in godoc, not user docs. Tables are only appropriate for comparing options or behaviors (sync modes, delivery approaches, config keys), not cataloguing API surface.
- **No internal method signatures in generated-code examples.** When illustrating what `golem-bake` emits, show the struct fields a developer reads and writes, not the interface methods the framework calls internally (`FlushUpdate`, `FullUpdate`, `MarshalUpdate`, `WorldName`, `Unmarshal`).
- **Exposing internals** that don't affect how a user calls the API. Implementation details like goroutine scheduling, template rendering, or internal data structure choices belong in contributor notes, not user docs. Never add contributor notes to user-facing pages.
- **Over-compressed** bullet lists that only name types and structs with no "why" or "when".
- Duplicating **subsystem rules** (`.cursor/rules/subsystem-*.mdc`); those target contributors, while user docs stay **task-oriented**.
- Adding **new** top-level markdown files (README, ADRs, extra indexes) unless the user asked for them; the website repo root **`README.md`** is only for repo-local Astro/Starlight workflow.
